## 1. What Is Private Credit? Plain English and Analogies

Think of private credit as a shadow mortgage market for businesses. Instead of companies borrowing from banks or issuing public bonds that anyone can buy on an exchange, they borrow directly from specialist funds — deals that are negotiated privately, never traded on any exchange, and priced using internal spreadsheet models rather than a live market.

> **Simple analogy.** Imagine a bank that lends money to risky small businesses, but instead of being regulated like a bank, it operates like a hedge fund. It raises money from pension funds and insurance companies, promises quarterly returns of 9–11%, and says "you can withdraw — but maybe not all at once." Nobody can see inside the loan book except the fund itself, and prices are set by an internal model that updates quarterly at best. That's private credit. Now imagine the fund tells pensioners that it is "low volatility" — which is technically true, because prices that don't move in real time *look* stable. That's the part that is currently unravelling.

The vehicles that hold these loans are called **Business Development Companies (BDCs)**. Some are publicly traded — you can buy ARCC or OBDC on the NYSE and see a live price. Many are "non-traded" — sold to wealthy retail investors and institutions with quarterly redemption windows but no live market price. The non-traded ones are where most current stress is concentrated, because there is no daily pricing signal telling investors what their holdings are worth.

### Why private credit looked attractive (or did)

Private credit loans typically yield 9–11%, versus 5–6% for investment-grade bonds. The extra return compensates for three things: (1) illiquidity — you can't easily sell the loan; (2) complexity — the deal is bespoke and hard to evaluate; (3) credit risk — the borrowers are too small or risky for banks. For a decade this tradeoff worked. NBER research (Matvos, Piskorski & Seru, March 2026) using comprehensive fund-level data confirms the structural strength: private credit funds carry 65–80% equity capital and have no maturity mismatch (10–12-year fund lives against 5–7-year loans). The critical caveat in the same research: the "low volatility" private credit advertised was partially artefactual — a product of marking loans at internal models that did not update with market reality, not genuine stability.

### Key terms you need before reading further

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **NAV (Net Asset Value)** | Book value of a fund's assets minus its liabilities, per share. If a BDC has $100 of loans and $40 of debt, NAV = $60. If the stock trades at $45, it's at a 25% discount to NAV — the market believes the loans are worth less than stated. |
| **PIK (Payment In Kind)** | When a borrower can't pay cash interest, it pays by adding more debt to what it owes. Warning sign: like a credit card where you defer payments by borrowing more. PIK ratio = % of total interest income received as additional debt rather than cash. Currently ~8% industry-wide; critical threshold is 10%. |
| **ICR (Interest Coverage Ratio)** | EBITDA ÷ interest expense. 2.0× means the company earns twice what it pays in interest. Below 1.0× means technically insolvent on an interest basis. Private credit software borrowers: average 1.4× (S&P Global). Broader PC universe: 1.7×. |
| **BDC (Business Development Company)** | A regulated fund created by Congress in 1980 to finance small businesses. BDCs can borrow up to 1× their equity (100% leverage cap under the 1940 Act). Public BDCs must disclose every loan quarterly. Non-traded BDCs offer periodic redemptions but no live price discovery. |
| **LTV (Loan-to-Value)** | Loan amount ÷ total enterprise value of the borrower. Blackstone's software loans average 37% LTV — 63% of the company's value must evaporate before Blackstone loses a dollar. Compare: subprime mortgages in 2008 were often 90–100% LTV. |
| **SOFR** | Secured Overnight Financing Rate, replacing LIBOR. Private credit loans are priced at "SOFR + 5–6%." When the Fed raises rates, borrower interest bills rise automatically with no renegotiation needed. This is good for lenders in rising-rate environments and catastrophic for over-leveraged borrowers. |
| **Gating / Redemption Gate** | When too many investors try to withdraw at once, a non-traded BDC caps redemptions at (typically) 5% per quarter. Investors who asked to redeem 40.7% (Blue Owl OTIC, April 2) receive only 5%. The rest stays locked. Gates are a contractual feature, not a failure — MS argues they are a "feature, not a bug," preventing fire sales. |
| **LME (Liability Management Exercise)** | A soft restructuring short of formal bankruptcy: modest principal haircut, incremental coupon, PE sponsor equity injection, maturity extension. Far easier in private credit (one lender) than BSL (50–75 CLOs must all agree). This bilateral flexibility is why MS projects 70–80% recovery rates rather than the 20–50% typical of BSL hard defaults. |
| **CDX.NA.HY** | A derivatives index tracking credit risk of 100 US high-yield companies. Buying protection (paying the spread) profits when corporate credit stress rises. HY spreads were 300bp in January 2026 — near historical tights. Currently ~380bp. |
| **BSL (Broadly Syndicated Loans)** | Large corporate loans originated by banks and sold to many institutional investors (typically 50–75 CLOs per loan). Has a functioning secondary market unlike private credit. The coordination failure in distressed BSL workouts is what makes recoveries structurally lower. |

