## 2. How Did It Get So Big? The Regulatory Origin

The short answer: post-2008 regulation created private credit.

After the global financial crisis, regulators imposed Basel III capital requirements and the **Liquidity Coverage Ratio (LCR)** on banks. These rules made it expensive for banks to hold leveraged middle-market loans — the capital charges were too high relative to returns. Banks retreated from anything above 6× EBITDA leverage. Private credit funds stepped into the vacuum.

**BIS researchers (Doerr, Gelos & Pursiainen, February 2026)** proved this causally using a natural experiment: US counties where more LCR-constrained banks operated saw significantly more private credit growth after LCR implementation. The effect magnitude was comparable to the capital shock from stress tests. **Private credit is, structurally, a $1.7 trillion regulatory arbitrage.**

Two important secondary transitions:

**Transition 1 (post-2012):** Banks pull back from 6×+ leverage deals. Private credit fills the high-leverage segment with an inherent quality bias toward weaker borrowers — exactly the ones banks avoided by regulatory mandate.

**Transition 2 (2022–2023):** Public credit markets tighten after the Fed's rate hiking cycle. New-issue access for high-leverage issuers became difficult. Private credit stepped in to refinance stressed public debt at par, absorbing borrowers who might otherwise have defaulted. Private credit financed over 80% of all LBO deals in 2025 (PitchBook/LCD).

**The Apollo-Athene flywheel amplified everything.** Apollo acquired Athene (a life insurance company) and used insurance policyholder deposits — retirement money — to fund private credit deals at scale. This flywheel has been replicated by KKR (Global Atlantic), FNF (F&G), and Brookfield. Result: nearly a third of the $6 trillion in US insurer assets is now allocated to private credit sub-asset classes. Retail savers are far more exposed to this market than their account statements suggest — but actual retail *equity* money in the system is approximately $200–250 billion of the $1.3 trillion US PC market (MS estimate), with 60%+ held by institutional investors in locked-up vehicles.

> **The forward implication for the trade:** The current administration is rolling back the same rules that created private credit. LCR interpretive FAQs were rescinded February 10, 2026. Basel III Endgame has been significantly softened. If banks re-enter middle-market lending, the structural driver of private credit's AUM growth partially reverses. Every alt-manager equity valuation assumes a 14% AUM CAGR. If the regulatory vacuum that created the asset class is closing, the correct forward CAGR is probably 5–7%. This structural headwind persists independent of the current default cycle.

