## 3. The Macro Frame: Compositional Risk, Not Aggregate Leverage

Before building the bear case, the single most important contextual correction — the one missing from most external commentary.

**Aggregate non-investment-grade corporate lending as a share of GDP is lower than pre-GFC.** Morgan Stanley's Exhibits 24–25 show US corporate debt/GDP declining consistently since 2020. The HY and loan markets have barely expanded since COVID. Even after accounting for all private credit fund growth, total sub-IG corporate lending relative to GDP sits below the 2006–2007 peak. In the years preceding the GFC, corporate leverage had been rising sharply and continuously. Today it has stabilised or declined.

**Private credit grew primarily by substituting for public credit, not by creating net new leverage.** A large portion of the 2022–2025 private credit AUM growth represents BSL borrowers refinancing into private channels at par — borrowers who would have defaulted or struggled without that option. What changed is who intermediates credit, not the aggregate risk in the system.

| Metric | Pre-GFC (2006–07) | Today (2025–26) |
|---|---|---|
| US corporate debt / GDP | ~55% and rising | ~42% and declining |
| Sub-IG credit / GDP | Rising sharply | Below pre-GFC |
| Private credit / GDP | Negligible | ~5% |
| Bank leverage (Tier 1) | 4–6% | 12–15% |
| BDC equity cushion | N/A | 65–80% equity capital (NBER) |

**The problem is compositional and structural, not systemic.** Worse borrowers have migrated into opaque, illiquidity-promising vehicles with quarterly redemption promises. The opacity prevents real-time price discovery. The retail capital in non-traded vehicles creates a redemption mismatch the system hasn't been stress-tested for. These are real vulnerabilities — but they are different from a system-wide leverage excess of the 2007 variety.

This framing determines the entire trade: this is not a short-the-system trade. It is a short-the-weakest-vehicles, long-the-strongest-managers trade.

