## 5. The Three Simultaneous Shocks

### Shock 1 — Iran, Oil, and the Rate Reversal

Operation Epic Fury (February 28, 2026) — US–Israel strikes on Iranian nuclear facilities — effectively closed the Strait of Hormuz to commercial traffic. The Strait carries 38% of global seaborne crude and 20% of global LNG. Brent crude moved from $70 to over $100 in weeks. GDP growth had already been revised to 0.7% in Q4 2025. Unemployment at 4.4%.

CME FedWatch flipped from 94% probability of two rate cuts (a month prior) to 19% probability of a rate *hike*. The 10-year Treasury moved from below 4% to 4.5%.

**The direct private credit transmission:** Almost all private credit loans are floating-rate, priced at SOFR + 5–6%. A 50bp rate increase adds $500M of annual interest expense to every $100B of floating-rate private credit. There is no hedge — borrowers absorb rate increases automatically. For a software company already at 1.4× ICR, a 50bp rate shock reduces coverage to approximately 1.2×, approaching the danger zone.

**Morgan Stanley's important nuance:** The softening in private credit sentiment actually predated Iran. The initial catalyst was the Fed moving toward rate cuts in H2 2025, which mechanically reduced income on floating-rate loans that had benefited from the higher-for-longer environment. Spread compression as public and private credit competed for the same borrowers had already eroded the illiquidity premium. Iran added a second, acute shock on top of an already-deteriorating return environment.

### Shock 2 — AI Disruption of the Software Sleeve

Software makes up approximately **26% of BDC collateral**, 20% of PC CLO collateral, and 16% of the BSL universe (Morgan Stanley Exhibit 3). It is the single largest sector in each market.

These loans were underwritten during 2020–2022 on ARR multiples, not EBITDA coverage. The thesis: SaaS businesses have sticky subscription revenue and high switching costs. That thesis is being tested: AI agents can now replicate what enterprise SaaS products do, at lower cost, reducing the stickiness that justified the lending.

**The credit quality is poor at entry.** Per S&P Global Ratings: software companies in the private credit universe carry average leverage of 8.0× vs. 6.6× for the broader universe, and interest coverage of 1.4× vs. 1.7× overall. Over 50% of BSL software loans are rated B- or lower. The 2021 vintage is disproportionately represented — software loan gross issuance peaked in 2021 at approximately $80B, and these are the borrowers now entering the sub-18-month refinancing window.

**Morgan Stanley's calibration:** AI will reshape software competition but will not eliminate the sector. There will be winners who integrate AI into products and see significant growth. The disruption is likely less imminent than the current market narrative implies — full AI disruption requires data centre infrastructure that is still being built (a multi-year capex program). **Refinancing risk will likely emerge before actual revenue disruption for many companies.** The default risk is primarily a maturity wall and capital access problem, not an immediate cash flow collapse.

**Morgan Stanley's software default estimate:** 15% sector-level BSL default rate; 20% sector-level private credit default rate, producing a total aggregate PC default rate of ~8% (2H26–1H27) when added to the current 5% in-place rate.

### Shock 3 — The BDC Liability Maturity Wall

BDCs borrow from banks against their loan portfolios ("back leverage") to juice returns. Approximately **$12.7B of BDC unsecured bonds mature in 2026 — up 73% versus 2025.**

They need to refinance this at a moment when: (a) underlying assets are being marked down; (b) PIK income is replacing cash income, reducing distributable earnings; and (c) bank credit lines are tightening as portfolio marks compress borrowing bases. JPMorgan preemptively marked down software loans in March 2026, directly compressing BDC borrowing capacity.

This is the mechanism that converts a liquidity problem into a solvency problem:

```
can't refinance → must sell assets → at a loss → marks fall further
     → borrowing base shrinks → forced to sell more → cycle repeats
```

Each lap of that loop is tighter than the last. The stabiliser is the gate: by preventing immediate forced liquidation, redemption caps break the loop and give managers time to meet redemptions through natural portfolio cash flows (loan repayments and refinancings). MS argues explicitly: "limits on redemption reduce the risk of forced selling, helping to prevent negative feedback loops and disorderly deleveraging."

