## 6. The Causal Chain — Seven Steps from Borrower Stress to Market Repricing

This is the section most commentary skips. The mechanism in precise order:

---

**Step 1 — Borrower stress accumulates silently (PIK)**

A mid-market SaaS company carrying $200M of private credit debt at SOFR + 575bp (approximately 11% all-in) sees ARR growth slow as AI reduces pricing power and customer churn rises. It cannot service full cash interest of $22M/year from operations. The lender — often the *sole* lender — negotiates a PIK toggle: the $22M annual interest payment is rolled into the principal. The BDC's loan balance grows from $200M to $222M. No cash comes in. PIK income share in the portfolio rises.

*Observable signal:* Quarterly BDC filings show % of investment income from PIK rising. Industry-wide now at 8%. Threshold to watch: 10%.

---

**Step 2 — BDC marks the loan down**

The BDC's valuation committee, advised by an independent third-party appraiser, marks the loan from $200M to $170M — it now believes full recovery is unlikely given the company's deteriorating revenue trajectory. NAV per share falls. Publicly traded BDC stock falls proportionally. Non-traded BDC investors read the quarterly report and submit redemption requests.

*The 90-day lag problem:* Current marks reflect Q3 2025 conditions. The Iran shock (February 28), the JPMorgan software markdown (March 2026), and Q1 2026 SaaS earnings deceleration are *not yet in any published BDC marks*. The first marks capturing all three shocks arrive in May 2026 filings.

---

**Step 3 — Redemption requests hit the gate**

The fund receives withdrawal requests for 20–40% of assets in a single quarter. It honors only 5% under its contractual gate. Investors who wanted out are stuck. News of the gate spreads. More investors submit requests — not because they believe the portfolio is bad, but because they want to be at the front of the queue for the next gate. The self-fulfilling dynamic begins.

*Morgan Stanley's assessment as of April 2026:* The redemption surge is "sentiment-driven rather than a fundamental downturn" — fund performance, default rates, non-accruals, and other metrics all appear very stable to date. The caveat: that could change as the cycle progresses and Q1 marks land.

*The BREIT precedent (MS Exhibits 48–49):* When BREIT gated in November 2022, it returned more than $15 billion before being able to meet 100% of requests again in early 2024 — a 15-month resolution period. Eventual stabilisation was driven by peaking interest rates and continued strong portfolio performance. BREIT reported its first net inflows since 2022 in February 2026. The template: gates protect assets, performance validates marks, redemption pressure abates.

---

**Step 4 — BDC sells assets or stops lending**

To fund any redemptions at all, the BDC must source cash. Options in declining order of desirability: (a) use portfolio cash flows from loan repayments and interest — adequate only if inflows roughly match redemption requests; (b) sell loans in the secondary market; (c) issue new equity — practically impossible in a distressed market.

Private credit loans have a thin secondary market — there is no exchange. A forced seller typically receives 80–95 cents on the dollar. Blue Owl sold $1.4B of loan assets across its credit vehicles at 99.7 cents on the dollar in Q1 — a remarkably clean sale that both funded redemptions and (critically) provided an observable market price confirming that marks were approximately correct.

For healthy borrowers: this credit supply withdrawal is manageable — they refinance via BSL or banks. For borrowers approaching maturity who need new capital: potentially fatal.

---

**Step 5 — Bank credit lines tighten (the borrowing-base amplifier)**

BDCs borrow from banks against diversified loan portfolios. Bank credit facilities are structured with **borrowing-base tests** — if portfolio asset values fall, the available credit line shrinks automatically. JPMorgan's March 2026 markdown of software loans compressed BDC borrowing bases immediately.

*This is where the math matters* — the amplifier is quantified precisely in Section 7. The short version: every $1 of BDC loan markdown forces approximately $0.67 of forced deleveraging. At the industry scale, this number is not trivial.

*The bank safety buffer:* However, from the *bank's* perspective, the look-through LTV is approximately 30% (see Section 9). The bank does not feel credit loss pressure until borrower enterprise values fall more than 70%. Bank credit line tightening is a headwind for BDCs, but it is not a risk to bank solvency.

---

**Step 6 — Insurance companies sit on hidden losses**

Apollo's Athene, KKR's Global Atlantic, and FNF's F&G hold private credit at **amortised cost** — they never mark to market. Their portfolios may be worth 10% less than stated, but neither regulators, rating agencies, nor policyholders can observe this. The loss only surfaces when: (a) they must sell (unlikely — insurance liabilities are long-duration); or (b) regulatory capital ratio tests catch it (slow, and subject to forbearance).

This is the insurance transmission channel that Morgan Stanley does not stress-test. See Section 10 for the full treatment.

---

**Step 7 — Stocks and broad credit reprice**

Alt-manager stocks fall because fee revenues compress with AUM. Public credit spreads widen because BDC forced selling hits the BSL secondary market — BDCs hold $143B of leveraged loans, more than all dedicated loan funds combined ($120B). Wider credit spreads raise borrowing costs for all leveraged companies, compressing equity multiples. Historically, **100bp of credit spread widening corresponds to 8–10% of equity multiple compression** on the S&P 500.

CDX.NA.HY spreads have moved from 300bp (January 2026, near historical tights) to approximately 380bp as of April 2026.

---

> **The binary from Chernenko & Scharfstein (Harvard/NBER stress test):**
> - If BDCs **can** sell loans: *zero funds* default on bank credit facilities even in a GFC-equivalent scenario
> - If BDCs **cannot** sell loans (contractual restrictions or no willing buyer): *20–35% of funds* enter technical default on bank credit lines
> - With bank forbearance: *almost all funds cure* within the stress period without realised bank losses
>
> The entire systemic risk question reduces to one binary: **loan sellability**. And the most important driver of sellability in private credit — which the academic literature agrees on — is that the single-lender bilateral structure makes LMEs far more accessible than in BSL, where 50–75 CLO holders must coordinate.

