## 10. The Three Bear Case Dimensions Morgan Stanley Does Not Resolve

Despite the calibrating power of the MS analysis, three dimensions of the bear case receive no meaningful treatment in their April 2 report. These remain the strongest arguments for sustained, multi-year impairment.

### 10.1 The Insurance Transmission Channel

MS discusses insurer exposure briefly but never stress-tests it. The aggregate: approximately one-third of the $6 trillion in US insurer invested assets is allocated across private credit sub-asset classes (JPMorgan Private Bank). PE-affiliated insurers — Athene (Apollo), Global Atlantic (KKR), F&G (FNF/Brookfield), Talcott (Sixth Street) — manage an estimated $1 trillion+ in assets through these relationships.

**The critical accounting distinction from banks:** Insurers carry private credit at *amortised cost*, not fair value. Losses accumulate silently in book values that never move until a capital ratio threshold is breached. An insurer portfolio that is worth 10% less than stated produces no visible signal — no mark-to-market loss, no earnings impact, no capital ratio movement — until either (a) they must sell assets (unlikely given long-duration liabilities), or (b) state insurance regulators run solvency tests that catch the impairment (slow, and subject to regulatory forbearance).

**The consequence:** Solvency erosion at PE-affiliated insurers constrains annuity issuance capacity, tightens the permanent capital available for new PE investment, and removes a key long-duration provider of credit capital from the system. This is a slow-burn, years-long channel — but it is real. UBS Chair Colm Kelleher has called the structure "akin to what banks did with subprime loans before the financial crisis" in terms of ratings arbitrage.

Unlike banks, which have FDIC oversight, Fed stress tests, and publicly visible mark-to-market provisioning, insurance solvency erosion will be detected by analysts long after it has already accumulated. This makes it the most dangerous of the three hidden channels.

### 10.2 The Knightian Uncertainty Discount on Unverifiable Marks

The academic literature (Matvos, Piskorski & Seru; Chernenko & Scharfstein; Wharton's Goldstein) converges on a point the MS practitioner report does not engage: **the core problem is not primarily credit losses but the impossibility of verifying whether marks are accurate in real time**.

Private credit funds mark quarterly using internal models and third-party appraisers. There is no secondary market to test the marks. Reporting lags by 90 days. The marks currently visible in BDC filings reflect December 2025 conditions — they do not capture the Iran shock (February 28), JPMorgan's software markdown (March 2026), or Q1 2026 SaaS revenue deceleration.

This creates what economists call **Knightian uncertainty** — not just "what are the losses" (calculable risk) but "can we even know what the losses are" (unknowable risk). The NAV discount decomposition in Section 7.4 shows this premium is approximately 21% of NAV — the dominant share of OBDC's discount is this unverifiability premium, not the fundamental credit loss estimate.

**The important implication:** This premium does not close when credit losses *resolve*. It closes when marks are *verified* by something that forces a cash settlement at an observable price. The verification events are: (a) forced loan sales in the secondary market (Blue Owl's $1.4B at 99.7¢ was informative); (b) May 2026 Q1 BDC filings showing stable ICR and PIK below the 10% threshold; (c) maturity events where principal is repaid or isn't.

**Wharton's Itay Goldstein** on why this matters: private credit is the current "shadow banking blind spot" — regulators don't have complete data on who owns what, at what leverage, funded by whom. The danger is in what nobody knows they own. If marks turn out to be materially wrong when finally verified, the repricing will be rapid and disorderly.

### 10.3 The LCR Reform Structural Headwind for AUM Growth

MS mentions deregulation as a bank tailwind but never completes the mirror logic for private credit AUM growth. The BIS causal paper (Doerr et al.) establishes that LCR introduction was comparably as powerful a driver of private credit growth as capital shocks from stress tests. If LCR reform proceeds — FAQs already rescinded, substantive rule revisions underway — the structural vacuum that generated the asset class begins to close.

**The implication for alt-manager equity valuations** is the most important argument that is not yet priced: even after the current default cycle resolves, the forward AUM growth rate for direct lending is structurally impaired by bank re-entry. Every alt-manager equity model assumes 12–14% AUM CAGR. The realistic forward rate, with banks re-entering middle-market lending, is probably 5–7%.

At 14% CAGR, an alt manager earning 1.5% management fees on $500B AUM reaches $1T in seven years, approximately doubling revenue. At 6% CAGR, they reach $750B in seven years — a much smaller revenue growth story. The multiple compression on alt manager equities is not just a credit cycle phenomenon; it is a structural growth story impairment. This is why the recovery trade in alt managers is BX, APO, and KKR (where direct lending is 3–7% of FPAUM), not a sector-wide bet.

