## 13. What Makes This Thesis Wrong? Honest Bull Scenarios

**Bull scenario 1 — Hormuz reopens quickly.** Peace negotiations succeed within weeks. Brent falls to $75. Fed returns to two-cut path. SOFR drops 50–75bp. ICR rebounds above 2.0× across the portfolio. Software defaults stay below 5%. The 25% NAV discount on OBDC closes to 10%. All alt manager stocks bounce 20–30%. This scenario does not require AI to stop disrupting software — just rate relief reducing the immediate ICR pressure that converts AI disruption from a gradual headwind into a near-term solvency event.

**Bull scenario 2 — AI earnings vindicate the boom.** Q1/Q2 hyperscaler revenue beats consensus. Enterprise SaaS companies demonstrate AI *augmentation* (selling AI tools built on their platforms) rather than AI *replacement*. Private credit software defaults stay 3–5%. The "25% of portfolios exposed to AI disruption" narrative is reframed as "25% of portfolios positioned for AI upside." Data-centre ABF thesis confirmed.

**Bull scenario 3 — May filings are clean.** Q1 2026 BDC filings (the first capturing all three shocks simultaneously) show ICR stable at 2.0×+ and PIK income below 8%. The 90-day lag that has been obscuring reality turns out to be obscuring resilience, not impairment. The unverifiability premium collapses rapidly. Quality BDCs (ARCC, BXSL, TSLX) rerate 15–25% within weeks of publication.

**Bull scenario 4 — Forbearance and bank patience.** Chernenko/Scharfstein show that bank forbearance resolves almost all technical covenant defaults within the stress period. The Fed and OCC quietly encourage forbearance for systemically important counterparties. The 20–35% technical default scenario resolves without realised losses. The system absorbs the stress slowly over 18–24 months — exactly as BREIT did — rather than liquidating rapidly.

**Bull scenario 5 — Rotation, not exodus.** KKR private wealth flows: $3.9B in Q1 2026, largely PE and infrastructure, with improving momentum into March. BXPE March gross flows were a monthly record. BREIT first net inflows since 2022 in February 2026. Money leaving private credit direct lending is rotating within alternatives to PE, infrastructure, and secondaries — not abandoning the alternative asset allocation. For diversified alt managers, this rotation is revenue-neutral or even revenue-positive.

> **The pattern that matters:** All five bull scenarios share a common feature — they either resolve the Hormuz/rate shock directly (scenarios 1 and 4) or provide enough time for the bilateral LME advantage to prevent hard defaults (scenarios 3, 4, and 5). None of the bull scenarios requires the AI thesis to be wrong. The trade is ultimately leveraged to the geopolitical binary of Middle East peace — and that concentration of scenario dependency in one exogenous event is itself a risk that should be hedged through position sizing.

