Direct lending to sub-investment-grade software companies reprices permanently — from a premium-yield asset class to one appropriately reflecting its credit risk. The industry consolidates around five to eight mega-managers with genuine origination moats, proprietary deal flow, and diversified credit strategies beyond direct lending. New loan vintages (2026–2027) will have tighter covenants, lower leverage, and smaller software weights — potentially among the strongest vintage years of the cycle, exactly as post-GFC vintages were.

Asset-backed finance overtakes direct lending in new-money flows. The insurance industry continues its shift toward ABF and private IG placements, replacing the high-yield direct lending exposure that is now under stress. LCR reform and Basel III Endgame rollback enable banks to return to middle-market lending, competing with private credit for the better-quality borrowers. AUM CAGR for direct lending resets to 5–7%.

Distressed fund LPs harvest 15–25% IRRs on 2026–2027 vintage positions. Quality BDC investors who bought at 2026 lows collect 10%+ yield while marks recover.

