## 16. Glossary

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **ABF (Asset-Backed Finance)** | Private credit loans backed by hard assets (aircraft, data centres, mortgages, auto loans) rather than corporate cash flows. Structurally safer because collateral can be sold regardless of borrower solvency. The "private credit 2.0" growth area. |
| **Amortised cost accounting** | Recording assets at original purchase price adjusted for amortisation, not current market value. Insurance companies use this — allowing PE-affiliated insurers to avoid marking private credit losses to market until capital ratio thresholds are breached. The slow-burn channel. |
| **ARR (Annual Recurring Revenue)** | Total predictable annual subscription revenue for SaaS businesses. Private credit funds underwrote 2020–2022 loans at "3–5× ARR" multiples without EBITDA. This is aggressive underwriting that works only if ARR persists at high margins. The thesis is breaking for commodity SaaS. |
| **Back leverage** | Bank loans extended to BDCs secured against their loan portfolios, allowing BDCs to invest more than their equity capital alone would permit. The borrowing-base amplifier (Section 7.1) operates through this mechanism. |
| **BDC (Business Development Company)** | A regulated fund structure created by Congress in 1980 to channel capital to small businesses. BDCs can borrow up to 1× equity (100% leverage cap under the 1940 Act). Public BDCs must disclose every loan quarterly. Non-traded BDCs offer periodic redemptions but no live price. |
| **Borrowing-base amplifier** | The feedback mechanism by which BDC loan markdowns force bank credit line reductions, which force loan sales, which depress prices, which trigger more markdowns. Formalised as ΔD = ΔA/δ where δ is the bank advance rate haircut. At δ = 1.5, every $1 of markdown forces $0.67 of forced deleveraging. |
| **BSL (Broadly Syndicated Loans)** | Large corporate loans originated by banks and sold to many institutional investors — typically 50–75 CLOs per loan. Has a functioning secondary market unlike private credit. The 50–75 holder coordination failure in distressed BSL workouts is why BSL recovery rates trend lower than private credit. |
| **Carry cost** | The ongoing annual cost of holding a derivative protection position. CDX.NA.HY protection at 380bp means paying 3.8%/year — expensive if spreads don't widen further. |
| **CLO (Collateralised Loan Obligation)** | Structured vehicle packaging loans into tranches with different risk/return profiles. 70% of BSL loans are held by CLOs, which are term-financed and not subject to redemption pressure. CLO issuance running at $45B in 2026 YTD — a positive signal for BSL market function. |
| **Covenant** | Contractual restriction on a borrower. Maintenance covenant: the borrower must maintain financial ratios (ICR, leverage) at all times, or the lender can demand repayment or renegotiate. BSL loans are largely covenant-lite. Private credit loans typically have strong maintenance covenants — a key structural advantage in restructuring. |
| **Distressed exchange (LME)** | A soft restructuring short of formal bankruptcy: modest principal haircut, incremental coupon, PE sponsor equity injection, maturity extension. 94% of private credit D-downgrades are LMEs (Morningstar DBRS). Far easier in private credit (one lender) than BSL. This is why MS projects 70–80% recovery rates. |
| **EBITDA** | Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation and Amortisation. Primary measure of operating cash generation used in credit underwriting. A company can be EBITDA-positive but cash-flow-negative after capex — the distinction matters for very high-growth SaaS businesses. |
| **Financial ouroboros** | A self-referential financial system where participants simultaneously invest in, borrow from, and sell to each other — inflating valuations without external demand validation. Applied to AI sector circular financing: Nvidia/OpenAI/Oracle/AMD reciprocal investment relationships that recycle capital without external demand validation. |
| **ICR (Interest Coverage Ratio)** | EBITDA ÷ interest expense. 2.0× = earns twice what it pays. Below 1.0× = technically cannot service debt. Private credit software borrowers average 1.4× (S&P Global). The threshold below which hard defaults become likely: approximately 1.2×. |
| **Knightian uncertainty** | Risk that cannot be quantified because the underlying probabilities are unknown — distinct from calculable risk. Applies to private credit marks: not just "what are the losses" but "can we even know what they are in real time?" The rational basis for the ~21% unverifiability premium in OBDC's NAV discount. |
| **LBO (Leveraged Buyout)** | Acquisition using primarily debt, often 5–6× EBITDA. PE sponsors used LBOs heavily in software (2020–2022 vintage). Private credit financed 80%+ of LBOs in 2025. PE dry powder globally: ~$2.7T. Sponsors have strong incentive to negotiate LMEs rather than walk away from invested equity. |
| **LCR (Liquidity Coverage Ratio)** | Basel III rule requiring banks to hold enough liquid assets to survive a 30-day stress event. BIS causally identifies LCR as a primary driver of private credit growth comparable in magnitude to capital shocks. LCR reform = structural AUM headwind for private credit. |
| **LME — see Distressed exchange** | |
| **Look-through LTV** | The effective loan-to-value ratio from a *bank's* perspective when lending to a BDC. Calculated as: borrower LTV × bank advance rate. At typical private credit underwriting (50% borrower LTV) and typical advance rates (60%), the bank look-through LTV is 30%. Enterprise value must fall more than 70% before the bank loses money. |
| **NAV (Net Asset Value)** | Book value of fund assets minus liabilities, per share. The NAV discount = (market price − NAV) / NAV. Driven by credit loss expectations and unverifiability premium. Closes when marks are verified, not when losses resolve. |
| **NDFI (Non-Depository Financial Institution)** | Bank regulatory category for lending to financial institutions that don't take deposits. Includes BDCs, CLO vehicles, PE funds, leasing companies. Private credit is the "business credit intermediaries" sub-component at 2.8% of total industry loans. Much of the 2024–2025 apparent NDFI growth is FDIC reclassification from C&I. |
| **Non-accrual** | A loan where the BDC has stopped accruing interest income because the borrower cannot pay. Disclosed quarterly in public BDC filings. The leading indicator for eventual write-offs and NAV impairment. |
| **PIK (Payment In Kind)** | When a borrower defers cash interest by adding principal. Industry-wide PIK share: ~8% of total investment income. Threshold: 10% signals approaching hard defaults. Above 10% historically precedes hard defaults by 1–2 quarters. |
| **Recovery rate** | Cents per dollar recovered when a borrower defaults. Private credit: ~70–80% (MS) due to strong covenants + bilateral LME advantage. BSL first liens: declining toward $59 (Moody's). Pure ARR-model SaaS in AI disruption scenario: potentially 20–40%. The swing variable in every scenario table. |
| **SaaS (Software as a Service)** | Subscription-based software. Historically characterised by recurring revenue and high switching costs — the features that justified private credit underwriting at 8× leverage. The switching cost thesis is being challenged by AI agents that replicate SaaS functionality at lower cost. |
| **SOFR** | Secured Overnight Financing Rate, replacing LIBOR. Private credit loans priced at SOFR + 500–600bp. Fed rate movements flow directly to borrower interest bills with no lag or renegotiation. |
| **Unverifiability premium** | The component of a BDC's NAV discount attributable to the impossibility of verifying marks in real time — the Knightian uncertainty premium. Approximately 21% of NAV in OBDC. Closes when observable cash transactions (forced loan sales, maturity repayments, quarterly filings) verify or refute the internal marks. |

